00:40:08.410 --> 00:40:09.280 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:09.280 --> 00:40:10.150 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:40:10.150 --> 00:40:11.700 align:middle line:90%
What is that?

00:40:11.700 --> 00:40:13.343 align:middle line:90%
>> I have no idea.

00:40:13.343 --> 00:40:15.760 align:middle line:84%
>> At first I thought it was
a ciliate lined with bacteria

00:40:15.760 --> 00:40:17.160 align:middle line:90%
but it's not.

00:40:17.160 --> 00:40:18.190 align:middle line:90%
It's something else.

00:40:18.190 --> 00:40:25.380 align:middle line:90%


00:40:25.380 --> 00:40:26.180 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:40:26.180 --> 00:40:26.920 align:middle line:90%
>> Oh my god.

00:40:26.920 --> 00:40:27.720 align:middle line:90%
>> It is.

00:40:27.720 --> 00:40:29.240 align:middle line:90%
It is the ciliate.

00:40:29.240 --> 00:40:30.680 align:middle line:90%
It's the ciliate, no?

00:40:30.680 --> 00:40:33.500 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:40:33.500 --> 00:40:35.500 align:middle line:84%
But what's interesting
about this particular one

00:40:35.500 --> 00:40:36.940 align:middle line:84%
is the surface of
it is completely

00:40:36.940 --> 00:40:38.740 align:middle line:90%
covered with little bacteria.

00:40:38.740 --> 00:40:40.160 align:middle line:90%
See each of these is a bacteria.

00:40:40.160 --> 00:40:41.782 align:middle line:90%
You can see some are dividing.

00:40:41.782 --> 00:40:43.240 align:middle line:84%
That one's just
starting to divide.

00:40:43.240 --> 00:40:45.350 align:middle line:84%
That one's almost
completely divided.

00:40:45.350 --> 00:40:46.150 align:middle line:90%
These are dividing.

00:40:46.150 --> 00:40:47.380 align:middle line:90%
So we know they're growing.

00:40:47.380 --> 00:40:49.780 align:middle line:90%
They're not just stuck there.

00:40:49.780 --> 00:40:52.120 align:middle line:84%
>> The very first time when
we looked at these pieces

00:40:52.120 --> 00:40:54.120 align:middle line:84%
of plastic-- now remember
these are really tiny,

00:40:54.120 --> 00:40:58.840 align:middle line:84%
probably half the size
of my pinky nail--

00:40:58.840 --> 00:41:03.010 align:middle line:84%
what we saw were some very
fascinating, basically little

00:41:03.010 --> 00:41:05.860 align:middle line:84%
worlds, if you will,
of microbial life.

00:41:05.860 --> 00:41:07.120 align:middle line:90%
We found predators.

00:41:07.120 --> 00:41:08.740 align:middle line:90%
We found prey.

00:41:08.740 --> 00:41:11.350 align:middle line:84%
We found organisms
that will actually

00:41:11.350 --> 00:41:14.710 align:middle line:84%
parasitize other organisms
and even symbiotes.

00:41:14.710 --> 00:41:16.540 align:middle line:84%
So this told us
that it was really

00:41:16.540 --> 00:41:18.730 align:middle line:84%
a self-sustaining
little ecosystem that

00:41:18.730 --> 00:41:21.190 align:middle line:84%
was floating out there in
the ocean gyres and garbage

00:41:21.190 --> 00:41:21.990 align:middle line:90%
patches.

00:41:21.990 --> 00:41:27.940 align:middle line:90%


00:41:27.940 --> 00:41:30.730 align:middle line:84%
>> They discovered
a world in itself,

00:41:30.730 --> 00:41:34.000 align:middle line:84%
an ecosystem that
existed alongside others,

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:37.450 align:middle line:84%
special communities different
to those that developed

00:41:37.450 --> 00:41:40.000 align:middle line:84%
on a natural medium
such as wood or algae.

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:44.930 align:middle line:90%


00:41:44.930 --> 00:41:47.330 align:middle line:84%
And among the
organisms identified

00:41:47.330 --> 00:41:50.660 align:middle line:84%
on the pieces of plastic,
one of them is intriguing.

00:41:50.660 --> 00:41:53.860 align:middle line:90%


00:41:53.860 --> 00:41:56.720 align:middle line:84%
>> And one of the first pieces
of microplastics that we

00:41:56.720 --> 00:41:59.990 align:middle line:84%
characterized the bacterial
communities on, we found that

00:41:59.990 --> 00:42:03.020 align:middle line:84%
there were very large
numbers of these vibrios.

00:42:03.020 --> 00:42:05.480 align:middle line:84%
And vibrios are interesting
because some of them,

00:42:05.480 --> 00:42:06.860 align:middle line:84%
not all of them,
but some of them

00:42:06.860 --> 00:42:09.245 align:middle line:84%
cause disease in
animals and humans.

00:42:09.245 --> 00:42:13.520 align:middle line:90%


00:42:13.520 --> 00:42:18.200 align:middle line:84%
>> Vibrio bacteria constituted
up to 25% of the microbial

00:42:18.200 --> 00:42:20.240 align:middle line:90%
cover of a piece of plastic.

00:42:20.240 --> 00:42:23.150 align:middle line:84%
And some of them are
known to carry cholera.

00:42:23.150 --> 00:42:26.210 align:middle line:84%
This finding requires
at least some attention.

00:42:26.210 --> 00:42:37.500 align:middle line:90%


00:42:37.500 --> 00:42:41.880 align:middle line:84%
>> Tracy Mincer, associated
with Linda and Eric's research,

00:42:41.880 --> 00:42:46.140 align:middle line:84%
has shown that the vibrios had
specific attachment mechanisms

00:42:46.140 --> 00:42:49.410 align:middle line:84%
which allow them to stick to
plastic very quickly and very

00:42:49.410 --> 00:42:52.320 align:middle line:90%
well.

00:42:52.320 --> 00:42:55.770 align:middle line:84%
These bacteria also have
genetic characteristics

00:42:55.770 --> 00:42:57.690 align:middle line:84%
that allow them to
attach themselves

00:42:57.690 --> 00:43:01.470 align:middle line:84%
to fish's intestinal tissue,
causing a real danger

00:43:01.470 --> 00:43:03.720 align:middle line:90%
to fish stocks.

00:43:03.720 --> 00:43:09.210 align:middle line:84%
>> They don't have the really
serious pathogenic abilities

00:43:09.210 --> 00:43:11.460 align:middle line:90%
that would affect humans.

00:43:11.460 --> 00:43:14.370 align:middle line:84%
And it makes sense because
these vibrios are not

00:43:14.370 --> 00:43:15.750 align:middle line:90%
interacting with humans at all.

00:43:15.750 --> 00:43:17.490 align:middle line:90%
They're interacting with fish.

00:43:17.490 --> 00:43:19.440 align:middle line:84%
And so what we think
might be happening

00:43:19.440 --> 00:43:25.950 align:middle line:84%
is that the plastic could serve
as a vector for these vibrios

00:43:25.950 --> 00:43:29.670 align:middle line:84%
to get around, and
get into other fish,

00:43:29.670 --> 00:43:34.465 align:middle line:84%
and transmit a parasitic or
pathogenic burden to fish

00:43:34.465 --> 00:43:35.265 align:middle line:90%
stocks.

00:43:35.265 --> 00:43:39.040 align:middle line:90%


00:43:39.040 --> 00:43:43.210 align:middle line:84%
>> A Trojan horse for
pathogenic bacteria and a raft

00:43:43.210 --> 00:43:45.130 align:middle line:90%
for invasive species.

00:43:45.130 --> 00:43:47.380 align:middle line:84%
These microplastics
could be the vector

00:43:47.380 --> 00:43:52.330 align:middle line:84%
for significant transformations
in the marine environment.

00:43:52.330 --> 00:43:56.170 align:middle line:84%
Studies are in their infancy
and yet scientists are already

00:43:56.170 --> 00:43:57.970 align:middle line:84%
alerting us to the
danger that they

00:43:57.970 --> 00:44:00.100 align:middle line:84%
could be harmful
for the equilibrium

00:44:00.100 --> 00:44:01.571 align:middle line:90%
of this environment.

00:44:01.571 --> 00:44:09.120 align:middle line:90%


00:44:09.120 --> 00:44:12.390 align:middle line:84%
But when observing these
microbial communities,

00:44:12.390 --> 00:44:14.460 align:middle line:84%
the three American
researchers also

00:44:14.460 --> 00:44:17.280 align:middle line:84%
made another
surprising discovery.

00:44:17.280 --> 00:44:19.530 align:middle line:84%
Some of the bacteria
have the ability

00:44:19.530 --> 00:44:22.275 align:middle line:84%
to accelerate the process
of decay of the plastic.

00:44:22.275 --> 00:44:26.670 align:middle line:90%


00:44:26.670 --> 00:44:31.620 align:middle line:84%
>> A surprising finding was that
many of the microbes that we

00:44:31.620 --> 00:44:35.760 align:middle line:84%
were finding in the plastisphere
had also been found in oil

00:44:35.760 --> 00:44:40.260 align:middle line:84%
spills, for example, and other
hydrocarbon degradation types

00:44:40.260 --> 00:44:41.680 align:middle line:90%
of experiments.

00:44:41.680 --> 00:44:48.300 align:middle line:84%
And so we found that was really
compelling based on the idea

00:44:48.300 --> 00:44:52.350 align:middle line:84%
that microbes that are
associated with those plastics

00:44:52.350 --> 00:44:55.110 align:middle line:84%
may also have the
capability to degrade

00:44:55.110 --> 00:44:58.230 align:middle line:90%
plastics or those hydrocarbons.

00:44:58.230 --> 00:45:00.640 align:middle line:90%
We're still looking into that.

00:45:00.640 --> 00:45:03.570 align:middle line:84%
But there's some good
evidence by microscopy

00:45:03.570 --> 00:45:06.930 align:middle line:84%
that some of these
microbes are actually

00:45:06.930 --> 00:45:10.890 align:middle line:84%
able to accelerate the
weathering or the hydroloysis,

00:45:10.890 --> 00:45:14.720 align:middle line:84%
the breakdown of plastics in
the wild in the open ocean.

00:45:14.720 --> 00:45:25.320 align:middle line:90%


00:45:25.320 --> 00:45:27.300 align:middle line:84%
As in the scanning
electron micrographs,

00:45:27.300 --> 00:45:29.490 align:middle line:84%
we saw these things we
call the pit formers.

00:45:29.490 --> 00:45:32.610 align:middle line:84%
So these are little two to
four micrometer round cells,

00:45:32.610 --> 00:45:37.020 align:middle line:84%
spherical cells, that appear
to be embedded in pits

00:45:37.020 --> 00:45:39.180 align:middle line:90%
in the surface of the plastic.

00:45:39.180 --> 00:45:41.940 align:middle line:84%
Whether they're metabolizing
it or just physically

00:45:41.940 --> 00:45:44.970 align:middle line:84%
breaking it down by the way
they attach, we don't know.

00:45:44.970 --> 00:45:47.160 align:middle line:84%
But that's one piece of
evidence that they're

00:45:47.160 --> 00:45:49.800 align:middle line:84%
impacting the plastic and
perhaps breaking it down.

00:45:49.800 --> 00:45:53.062 align:middle line:90%


00:45:53.062 --> 00:45:54.330 align:middle line:90%
>> That makes sense.

00:45:54.330 --> 00:45:57.840 align:middle line:84%
>> Bacteria capable
of decaying plastic.

00:45:57.840 --> 00:46:01.030 align:middle line:84%
Eric, Linda, and Tracy
examined this question.

00:46:01.030 --> 00:46:02.970 align:middle line:84%
And there is now
no doubt that they

00:46:02.970 --> 00:46:06.060 align:middle line:84%
have a role in the fragmentation
of plastic in the oceans.

00:46:06.060 --> 00:46:14.110 align:middle line:90%


00:46:14.110 --> 00:46:18.010 align:middle line:84%
But are the bacteria able to
metabolize and therefore cause

00:46:18.010 --> 00:46:20.485 align:middle line:84%
the plastic to totally
disappear from our oceans?

00:46:20.485 --> 00:46:28.250 align:middle line:90%


00:46:28.250 --> 00:46:31.075 align:middle line:84%
Today there is evidence
that this is the case.

00:46:31.075 --> 00:46:36.800 align:middle line:90%


00:46:36.800 --> 00:47:17.730 align:middle line:90%
>> [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:47:17.730 --> 00:47:20.700 align:middle line:84%
>> In Banyuls-sur-Mer,
Jean-Francois Ghiglione

00:47:20.700 --> 00:47:24.270 align:middle line:84%
and Claire Dussud from the
Microbial Biology Laboratory

00:47:24.270 --> 00:47:28.140 align:middle line:84%
show that there are strains of
bacteria that, when isolated,

00:47:28.140 --> 00:47:32.490 align:middle line:84%
totally consume different types
of plastic from the ocean.

00:47:32.490 --> 00:47:35.580 align:middle line:84%
The bacteria have developed
a complex strategy

00:47:35.580 --> 00:47:37.740 align:middle line:90%
for ingesting the plastic.

00:47:37.740 --> 00:47:55.590 align:middle line:90%
>> [SPEAKING FRENCH]

00:47:55.590 --> 00:47:59.460 align:middle line:84%
>> It's a problem for bacteria
because these plastic particles

00:47:59.460 --> 00:48:02.670 align:middle line:90%
are not edible and are too big.

00:48:02.670 --> 00:48:05.670 align:middle line:84%
Bacteria, therefore,
start by sending enzymes

00:48:05.670 --> 00:48:08.430 align:middle line:84%
outside their cell
to oxidize them.

00:48:08.430 --> 00:48:10.920 align:middle line:84%
Once there is oxygen
on the polymer,

00:48:10.920 --> 00:48:14.070 align:middle line:84%
the bacteria send other
extracellular enzymes

00:48:14.070 --> 00:48:16.620 align:middle line:90%
to cut the chains of carbon.

00:48:16.620 --> 00:48:18.450 align:middle line:84%
Different species
of bacteria are

00:48:18.450 --> 00:48:20.850 align:middle line:84%
implicated in the
process of decay

00:48:20.850 --> 00:48:24.540 align:middle line:84%
until they are able to reduce
the polymer to small molecules

00:48:24.540 --> 00:48:25.790 align:middle line:90%
that they can finally consume.

00:48:25.790 --> 00:48:35.430 align:middle line:90%


00:48:35.430 --> 00:48:39.745 align:middle line:84%
Can bacteria explain why we
cannot find 99% of the plastic

00:48:39.745 --> 00:48:40.545 align:middle line:90%
in our oceans?

00:48:40.545 --> 00:48:44.388 align:middle line:90%


00:48:44.388 --> 00:48:46.055 align:middle line:84%
Could they be the
answer to the problem?

00:48:46.055 --> 00:48:48.860 align:middle line:90%


00:48:48.860 --> 00:48:51.050 align:middle line:84%
Claire and Jean-Francois
are working

00:48:51.050 --> 00:48:55.910 align:middle line:84%
to characterize the
microbial communities.

00:48:55.910 --> 00:49:00.050 align:middle line:84%
The process of decay of
plastic in the sea is complex.

00:49:00.050 --> 00:49:03.650 align:middle line:84%
Tens of thousands of bacteria
are implicated and follow

00:49:03.650 --> 00:49:08.090 align:middle line:84%
each other over time without us
knowing exactly who does what.

00:49:08.090 --> 00:49:54.080 align:middle line:90%
>> [SPEAKING FRENCH]

00:49:54.080 --> 00:49:56.870 align:middle line:84%
>> If bacteria can
absorb plastic,

00:49:56.870 --> 00:49:59.870 align:middle line:84%
they can still only
explain a tiny part of this

00:49:59.870 --> 00:50:01.520 align:middle line:90%
disappearance.

00:50:01.520 --> 00:50:03.320 align:middle line:84%
They are not the
miracle solution

00:50:03.320 --> 00:50:05.960 align:middle line:90%
to the mystery that remains.

00:50:05.960 --> 00:50:10.670 align:middle line:84%
Nature can adapt, but it cannot
follow our frantic consumption

00:50:10.670 --> 00:50:14.330 align:middle line:84%
and our inability to
manage the resulting waste.

00:50:14.330 --> 00:50:17.180 align:middle line:84%
For a few years now,
the scientific community

00:50:17.180 --> 00:50:20.690 align:middle line:84%
has tried to understand what
happens once plastic enters

00:50:20.690 --> 00:50:25.730 align:middle line:84%
the sea, questioning not only
its fate but also its effects.

00:50:25.730 --> 00:50:27.890 align:middle line:84%
They have identified
microplastics

00:50:27.890 --> 00:50:30.890 align:middle line:84%
as a source of preoccupation
and are already

00:50:30.890 --> 00:50:34.400 align:middle line:84%
wondering whether nanoplastics,
even smaller particles,

00:50:34.400 --> 00:50:35.300 align:middle line:90%
are not even worse.

00:50:35.300 --> 00:50:38.970 align:middle line:90%


00:50:38.970 --> 00:50:41.390 align:middle line:84%
But today we are still
measuring the time

00:50:41.390 --> 00:50:45.428 align:middle line:84%
and the rate of decay of
these plastics in our oceans.

00:50:45.428 --> 00:50:46.970 align:middle line:84%
>> We're very much
at the first step.

00:50:46.970 --> 00:50:49.550 align:middle line:84%
We're asking the
most basic questions.

00:50:49.550 --> 00:50:52.100 align:middle line:84%
We're just trying to assemble
all of the information

00:50:52.100 --> 00:50:55.490 align:middle line:84%
that we can find in
order to see if we

00:50:55.490 --> 00:50:56.750 align:middle line:90%
can answer these questions.

00:50:56.750 --> 00:50:58.370 align:middle line:90%
For the most part, we can't.

00:50:58.370 --> 00:51:03.080 align:middle line:84%
>> But on the other hand, we
do have some answers and some

00:51:03.080 --> 00:51:07.760 align:middle line:84%
knowledge about ways that we
could perhaps prevent plastic

00:51:07.760 --> 00:51:08.640 align:middle line:90%
entering the ocean.

00:51:08.640 --> 00:51:12.398 align:middle line:90%


00:51:12.398 --> 00:51:14.940 align:middle line:84%
>> Way to keep plastic out of
the ocean is to stop putting it

00:51:14.940 --> 00:51:15.740 align:middle line:90%
in there.

00:51:15.740 --> 00:51:20.010 align:middle line:84%
Stop it at the shore, the
rivers, the landfills,

00:51:20.010 --> 00:51:24.780 align:middle line:84%
the waste dumps, just
human choice basically.

00:51:24.780 --> 00:51:27.680 align:middle line:90%


00:51:27.680 --> 00:51:30.500 align:middle line:84%
>> So it's not about
not using plastics.

00:51:30.500 --> 00:51:33.470 align:middle line:84%
It's about using them
much more smartly.

00:51:33.470 --> 00:51:35.420 align:middle line:84%
And what that, in my
view, is going to take

00:51:35.420 --> 00:51:40.490 align:middle line:84%
is rethinking the
way we produce, use,

00:51:40.490 --> 00:51:43.190 align:middle line:90%
and dispose of plastics.

00:51:43.190 --> 00:51:45.560 align:middle line:84%
And the increasing realization
is that there really

00:51:45.560 --> 00:51:47.540 align:middle line:90%
isn't any away on the planet.

00:51:47.540 --> 00:51:52.010 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:51:52.010 --> 00:51:54.320 align:middle line:90%
>> We are living in a vacuum.

00:51:54.320 --> 00:51:57.730 align:middle line:84%
It is time to realize this
before this piece of art

00:51:57.730 --> 00:52:01.090 align:middle line:84%
that we come across by
chance in an airport morphs

00:52:01.090 --> 00:52:04.750 align:middle line:84%
into something more sinister,
no longer there to calm

00:52:04.750 --> 00:52:07.990 align:middle line:84%
the stressed out travelers
but to remind them of what

00:52:07.990 --> 00:52:10.560 align:middle line:90%
has become of our oceans.

00:52:10.560 --> 00:53:02.000 align:middle line:90%